  "text": "1) Low-risk liquidity (e.g. certain microfinance programmes) to those in the poverty trap, allowing poor households to accumulate assets, take advantage of returns to scale and overcome minimum barriers to entry for creating added value (e.g. cheese derived from milk) . 2) Risk transfer products (e.g. rainfall-indexed insurance) to all vulnerable populations to prevent households from slipping or falling further into the poverty trap [CITATION_1] .",
